{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588465"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:08:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:08:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15144"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15144"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.12,0.1,0.1,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7832"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68521"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7832"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15144"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53978"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"},{"type":"tags","id":"10845"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19096"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19099"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68521"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECertain bacteria can develop antibiotic resistance during treatment despite showing initial sensitivity on laboratory testing. This phenomenon is particularly important when treating serious infections.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following bacteria commonly demonstrates inducible resistance to cephalosporins despite initial sensitivity testing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Escherichia coli","Klebsiella pneumoniae","Enterobacter cloacae","Proteus mirabilis","Pseudomonas aeruginosa"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EInducible resistance to cephalosporins is an important clinical phenomenon that can lead to treatment failure despite apparent sensitivity on initial testing. \u003Cstrong\u003EEnterobacter cloacae\u003C/strong\u003E is the classic example of a bacterium that possesses inducible AmpC beta-lactamases. When exposed to certain beta-lactam antibiotics, these organisms can increase their production of AmpC enzymes, leading to resistance during treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/strong\u003E typically does not possess inducible beta-lactamases. While it can acquire resistance through other mechanisms, such as extended-spectrum beta-lactamases (ESBLs), this resistance is usually constitutive rather than inducible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKlebsiella pneumoniae\u003C/strong\u003E, like \u003Cem\u003EE. coli\u003C/em\u003E, can acquire various resistance mechanisms but does not typically demonstrate inducible resistance. Its resistance patterns are usually stable and detectable on initial testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProteus mirabilis\u003C/strong\u003E generally maintains stable susceptibility patterns and does not commonly demonstrate inducible resistance to cephalosporins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/strong\u003E can develop resistance through multiple mechanisms during treatment, but its primary mechanism is not through inducible beta-lactamases like those seen in \u003Cem\u003EEnterobacter\u003C/em\u003E species.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis phenomenon has important clinical implications. When treating infections caused by organisms known to possess inducible AmpC beta-lactamases, clinicians should be cautious about using third-generation cephalosporins even if initial susceptibility testing suggests sensitivity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Enterobacter cloacae possesses inducible AmpC beta-lactamases that can be activated during antibiotic treatment.","Initial antibiotic sensitivity testing may not detect inducible resistance mechanisms.","Treatment with certain beta-lactam antibiotics can trigger increased AmpC enzyme production, leading to resistance."],"references":["Paterson DL. Resistance in gram-negative bacteria: enterobacteriaceae. Am J Med. 2006 Jun;119(6 Suppl 1):S20-8; discussion S62-70. doi: 10.1016/j.amjmed.2006.03.013. PMID: 16735147.","Potz NA, Hope R, Warner M, Johnson AP, Livermore DM; London \u0026 South East ESBL Project Group. Prevalence and mechanisms of cephalosporin resistance in Enterobacteriaceae in London and South-East England. J Antimicrob Chemother. 2006 Aug;58(2):320-6. doi: 10.1093/jac/dkl217. Epub 2006 May 30. PMID: 16735428.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53978"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15144"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53978"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T19:57:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T19:57:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7832"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68521"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups